#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/apps-and-games.md:11
msgid "In KDE Linux, most software is packaged using a technology called [Flatpak](https://flatpak.org/) and distributed through https://flathub.org. You can get this software in two ways: graphically using the _Discover_ software center app, or using the <code>flatpak</code> command-line tool."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/apps-and-games.md:14 content/docs/updates.md:14
msgid "Graphical"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/apps-and-games.md:15
msgid "_Discover_ is the primary tool for getting new software on KDE Linux. It’s very easy to use; just launch it! You can use the search field to find something specific, or browse through one of the categories in the sidebar on the left side of the window."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/apps-and-games.md:17
msgid "Discover includes productivity apps as well as games; many games are available directly through Discover, plus emulators and game downloaders/launchers like Steam, which can be used to get even more games."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/apps-and-games.md:20 content/docs/updates.md:22
msgid "Command-line"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/apps-and-games.md:21
msgid "The <code>flatpak</code> command-line tool can be run in a terminal window to interact with the world of Flatpak apps. Here are some examples of basic usage:"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/apps-and-games.md:23
msgid "To search for apps to install, run <code>flatpak search [search term]</code>."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/apps-and-games.md:24
msgid "To install an app, run <code>flatpak install [id of the app you want to install, expressed in reverse-dns format, e.g. org.kde.kstars]</code>."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/apps-and-games.md:25
msgid "To see what’s installed, run <code>flatpak list</code>."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/apps-and-games.md:26
msgid "To uninstall an app, run <code>flatpak uninstall [id of the app you want to remove, expressed in reverse-dns format, e.g. org.kde.kstars]</code>."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/apps-and-games.md:28
msgid "To learn more, run <code>flatpak --help</code>."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/apps-and-games.md:31
msgid "I can’t find something there that I know exists!"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/apps-and-games.md:32
msgid "It’s probably not packaged as a Flatpak yet. What a shame! Consider contacting the software’s authors and asking them to package it as a Flatpak on Flathub."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/apps-and-games.md:34
msgid "In the meantime, see [this page](more-software) for some options regarding what to do next."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/apps-and-games.md:0
msgid "Install Apps and Games"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/automount.md:11
msgid "If your computer includes multiple internal disks, only the one containing the boot volume will be automatically mounted at login. It can be useful to auto-mount other ones, too. Here’s how to do so:"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/automount.md:13
msgid "Launch the _System Settings_ app"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/automount.md:14
msgid "In the sidebar list, click “Disks & Cameras”"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/automount.md:15
msgid "In the new sidebar list, click “Device Auto-mount”"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/automount.md:16
msgid "In the main view, click the checkbox for “On Login” on the row of each disk you want to auto-mount"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/automount.md:17
msgid "Click “Apply”"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/automount.md:0
msgid "Auto-Mount Internal Disks"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/background.md:13
msgid "Veteran KDE developer Harald Sitter began working on KDE Linux in early 2023, and revealed its working prototype at Akademy 2024 ([slides](https://conf.kde.org/event/6/contributions/202/attachments/135/171/The%20Operating%20System.pdf), [recording](http://www.youtube.com/live/gTxRaBEUe-I?t=25936))."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/background.md:15
msgid "An [alpha release](https://pointieststick.com/2025/09/06/announcing-the-alpha-release-of-kde-linux/) followed at Akademy 2025 ([slides](https://conf.kde.org/event/9/contributions/265/attachments/171/220/growth.pdf), [recording](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=PA03J1CAYoA))."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/background.md:17
msgid "The project incorporates lessons learned from the earlier [KDE neon](https://neon.kde.org/) project, and focuses on resilience, modern technical infrastructure, and low maintenance needs. KDE Linux’s design is heavily inspired by systemd creator Lennart Poettering’s thoughts on [OS design](https://0pointer.net/blog/fitting-everything-together.html) and [system extensions](https://0pointer.net/blog/testing-my-system-code-in-usr-without-modifying-usr.html)."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/background.md:0
msgid "History & Architecture"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/backup.md:11
msgid "KDE Linux includes a built-in system to back up your important data to a secondary disk or a network location."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/backup.md:13
msgid "To set this up, do the following:"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/backup.md:15
msgid "Open the *System Settings* app and click on *Backups*, at the bottom of the sidebar’s *System* group."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/backup.md:16
msgid "Click *Add New Plan…*"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/backup.md:17
msgid "Click *Destination* and choose where to store the backup. There are two options:"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/backup.md:18
msgid "**External storage disk:** plug it in, click *Mount and Open* in the popup that appears, click *External Storage* on the backup destination page, and select the disk in the list."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/backup.md:19
msgid "**Network location:** make sure it’s manually mounted using `/etc/fstab` and then select it in *Destination Path for Backup:*"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/backup.md:20
msgid "Click *Schedule* and choose a schedule."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/backup.md:21
msgid "Click *Apply*."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/backup.md:23
msgid "Thereafter, your data will be periodically saved to the configured location. This system will keep multiple old versions of the data until the location fills up, and then remove the oldest versions."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/backup.md:0
msgid "Back Up Data"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/boot-failure-recovery.md:11
msgid "It can be quite distressing when a computer fails to boot up normally! Here are some recovery mechanisms:"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/boot-failure-recovery.md:14
msgid "Roll back to an older version of the operating system (OS)"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/boot-failure-recovery.md:15
msgid "If the boot failure started happening after you updated the system, rolling back to the older version will generally fix it."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/boot-failure-recovery.md:17 content/docs/char-input.md:69
msgid "To do this:"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/boot-failure-recovery.md:18
#: content/docs/boot-failure-recovery.md:35
msgid "Power on or restart the machine."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/boot-failure-recovery.md:19
#: content/docs/boot-failure-recovery.md:36
msgid "Hold down <kbd>Space</kbd> until the OS version chooser appears (in white text in the center of the screen, against a black background)."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/boot-failure-recovery.md:20
msgid "Press the down arrow key once to select the prior OS version, or a different one."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/boot-failure-recovery.md:21
msgid "Press <kbd>Enter</kbd> to boot into it."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/boot-failure-recovery.md:23
msgid "If this fixes the issue, please report it at https://invent.kde.org/kde-linux/kde-linux/-/issues/, and attach the output of running <code>journalctl --boot -1 --no-pager</code> in a terminal window."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/boot-failure-recovery.md:26
msgid "Boot the system in a different way by changing the kernel command line"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/boot-failure-recovery.md:27
msgid "{{< section class=\"text-center warning-bubble\" >}} Be careful with the options presented here! If you are not a technical expert and don’t know what you’re doing, using these tools can easily make the problem even worse. {{< /section >}}"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/boot-failure-recovery.md:31
msgid "If that does not work, you can change how the system boots by altering the kernel command line parameters to achieve various debugging approaches."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/boot-failure-recovery.md:33
msgid "To edit the kernel command line:"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/boot-failure-recovery.md:37
msgid "Press the <kbd>e</kbd> key."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/boot-failure-recovery.md:38
msgid "A text field with very long text in it will appear; this is the kernel command line."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/boot-failure-recovery.md:41
msgid "Disable systemd extensions"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/boot-failure-recovery.md:42
msgid "Add <code>systemd.mask=systemd-sysext.service</code>to the kernel command line and then press <kbd>Enter</kbd>."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/boot-failure-recovery.md:44
msgid "This is useful if you have any systemd extensions active, and the boot failure started happening after you updated the content in any of them; this could be the cause. Temporarily disabling extensions should resolve the issue until you can debug what’s wrong with it."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/boot-failure-recovery.md:47
msgid "If this works, after logging in, debug what’s wrong with the extension and fix it. If you are unable to, disable it."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/boot-failure-recovery.md:50
msgid "Bypass issues with the login screen or Plasma"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/boot-failure-recovery.md:51
msgid "Add <code>systemd.unit=multi-user.target</code> to the kernel command line and then press <kbd>Enter</kbd>."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/boot-failure-recovery.md:53
msgid "This is useful if the login screen or plasma are failing to start or crashing in a loop; you can boot into a command-line environment that will bypass both of them, within which debugging is possible."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/boot-failure-recovery.md:55
#: content/docs/boot-failure-recovery.md:65
msgid "If debugging and troubleshooting determines that the problem was not caused by your own actions, [open a bug report for the KDE Linux team](https://invent.kde.org/kde-linux/kde-linux/-/issues/) to investigate."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/boot-failure-recovery.md:58
msgid "Enter the emergency root shell"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/boot-failure-recovery.md:59
msgid "Add <code>systemd.debug_shell=on SYSTEMD_SULOGIN_FORCE=1</code> to the kernel command line and press <kbd>Enter</kbd>."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/boot-failure-recovery.md:60
msgid "Wait for the screen to turn black and stay that way for a few seconds."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/boot-failure-recovery.md:61
msgid "Press <kbd>Ctrl</kbd>+<kbd>Alt</kbd>+<kbd>F9</kbd> (note: on a laptop, you may also have to hold down <kbd>Fn</kbd>)."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/boot-failure-recovery.md:63
msgid "You are now in the *emergency root shell*. Every command you run will be executed as root, so be careful."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/boot-failure-recovery.md:68
msgid "Roll back `/etc`"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/boot-failure-recovery.md:69
msgid "It’s possible for `/etc` to be modified when booted into a particular build in a way that makes it incompatible with older builds."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/boot-failure-recovery.md:71
msgid "This can manifest as bizarre issues after rolling back the OS, such as black screens or login passwords not being accepted."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/boot-failure-recovery.md:73
msgid "To recover, replace the broken `/etc` with an older, working one as follows:"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/boot-failure-recovery.md:75
msgid "Get a shell via either of the above methods and run the following commands:"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/boot-failure-recovery.md:76
msgid "<code>sudo mv /etc /etc.broken</code>"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/boot-failure-recovery.md:77
msgid "<code>sudo btrfs subvolume snapshot $(ls -d -1 /.etc.* | tail -2 | head -1) /etc</code>"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/boot-failure-recovery.md:78
msgid "<code>systemctl reboot</code>"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/boot-failure-recovery.md:80
msgid "These manual steps should become unnecessary once https://invent.kde.org/kde-linux/kde-linux/-/issues/505 is implemented."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/boot-failure-recovery.md:83 content/docs/flatpak-crashes.md:26
msgid "Further information"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/boot-failure-recovery.md:84
msgid "See https://systemd.io/DEBUGGING for more debugging options. KDE Linux uses systemd exclusively, so everything on that page is relevant."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/boot-failure-recovery.md:0
msgid "Recover from Boot Failures"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/char-input.md:11
msgid "How do you type a `€` character when your keyboard only has `$` on it? Or maybe you need `è`, `é`, or `ñ`. What about a fancy `°` degree sign? And how about emojis? Technically those are characters, too!"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/char-input.md:13
msgid "KDE Linux offers multiple ways:"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/char-input.md:16
msgid "KCharSelect"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/char-input.md:17
msgid "*Easy to learn, but slow to use.*"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/char-input.md:19
msgid "The [*KCharSelect*](https://apps.kde.org/kcharselect/) app lets you visually search and browse through the entire catalog of characters available across all languages — including emojis. Once you’ve found the appropriate character, you can copy it to the clipboard for pasting elsewhere."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/char-input.md:21
msgid "*KCharSelect* is not pre-installed, but can be installed using the *Discover* software center."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/char-input.md:23
msgid "<a href=\"appstream://org.kde.kcharselect\">Install KCharSelect now</a>"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/char-input.md:26
msgid "Emoji Picker"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/char-input.md:27
msgid "*Easy to learn and fast to use, but limited to emojis.*"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/char-input.md:29
msgid "KDE Linux includes the *Emoji Picker* app which offers a more streamlined emoji-picking experience compared to using *KCharSelect*. To launch it from anywhere, press <kbd>Meta</kbd>+<kbd>.</kbd>."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/char-input.md:31
msgid "From there, you can search or browse for an emoji, and click on it to copy it to the clipboard for pasting elsewhere. *Emoji Picker* automatically remembers the last emojis you used, too."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/char-input.md:34
msgid "On-demand character palette"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/char-input.md:35
msgid "*Easy to learn and fast to use, but only has partial coverage for symbols, and no emojis.*"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/char-input.md:37 content/docs/char-input.md:70
msgid "Open *System Settings*"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/char-input.md:38
msgid "Navigate to *Keyboard* > *Virtual Keyboard*"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/char-input.md:39
msgid "Click *Plasma Keyboard* and click *Apply*"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/char-input.md:41
msgid "Now, whenever you’d like to type an accented character, press and hold the key on your physical keyboard that looks closest to it."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/char-input.md:43
msgid "For example, if you want `é`, press and hold the <kbd>e</kbd> key."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/char-input.md:45
msgid "In a moment, a pop-up will appear showing possible accented characters. Select the one you want by clicking on it, pressing the number key below it, or navigating to it using the arrow keys and pressing <kbd>Enter</kbd>"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/char-input.md:48
msgid "Compose Key"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/char-input.md:49
msgid "*Very fast to use, but requires some learning, and no emojis.*"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/char-input.md:51
msgid "See how the Euro symbol (`€`) looks kind of like the letter C with an equals sign through it?"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/char-input.md:53
msgid "To type `€` directly, press the <kbd>Compose</kbd> key, then <kbd>C</kbd>, then <kbd>=</kbd>."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/char-input.md:55
msgid "Easy!"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/char-input.md:57
msgid "Similarly, to get `é`, press <kbd>Compose</kbd>, then <kbd>e</kbd>, then <kbd>'</kbd>."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/char-input.md:59
msgid "`ñ` is made with <kbd>Compose</kbd>, <kbd>n</kbd>, <kbd>~</kbd>."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/char-input.md:61
msgid "`°` is made with <kbd>Compose</kbd>, <kbd>o</kbd>, <kbd>o</kbd>"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/char-input.md:63
msgid "`…` is made with <kbd>Compose</kbd>, <kbd>.</kbd>, <kbd>.</kbd>"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/char-input.md:65
msgid "…And so on."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/char-input.md:67
msgid "But which key is the <kbd>Compose</kbd> key? Your keyboard probably doesn’t have one. In this case, you’ll need to re-bind an existing key you rarely or never use to act as a <kbd>Compose</kbd> key."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/char-input.md:71
msgid "Click *Keyboard* in the sidebar"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/char-input.md:72
msgid "Click *Key Bindings* in the window header"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/char-input.md:73
msgid "Scroll down to where it says *Position of Compose Key* and click on it"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/char-input.md:74
msgid "Choose a key to be your new <kbd>Compose</kbd> key! Some keys that are good candidates because they are otherwise rarely used are <kbd>Caps Lock</kbd>, <kbd>Insert</kbd>, <kbd>Pause</kbd>, and <kbd>Scroll Lock</kbd>."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/char-input.md:76
msgid "Compose key sequences are generally intuitive, but to see the full list of options, open a terminal window and run:"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/char-input.md:78
msgid "<code>rg Multi_key /usr/share/X11/locale/en_US.UTF-8/Compose | cut -d \"\\\\\"\" -f 1,2</code>"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/char-input.md:0
msgid "Type Characters Not On Your Keyboard"
msgstr ""

