msgid "*File > New Virtual Machine > Import existing disk image*. Click the *Forward* button."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/install-vm.md:47
msgid "In *Provide the existing storage path: > Browse*, find raw file that you downloaded. Click the *Choose Volume* button."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/install-vm.md:48
msgid "In *Choose the operating system you are installing:* write *Arch Linux*. Click the *Forward* button."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/install-vm.md:49
msgid "In *Choose Memory and CPU settings:*, choose CPU count (minimum 2, ideally 4+) and memory (minimum 2 GB, ideally 4+). Click the *Forward* button."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/install-vm.md:50
msgid "Enable the checkbox *Customize configuration before install*. Click the *Finish* button."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/install-vm.md:51
msgid "The configuration window for the new VM is opened. In *Overview > Details > Firmware:* select *UEFI*."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/install-vm.md:52
msgid "On the bottom left, click the button *Add Hardware*."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/install-vm.md:53
msgid "Add a storage disk of some reasonable size. E.g. Storage > Details tab > select the radio button *Create a disk image for the virtual machine* and set the disk size to at least 15 GB, ideally more than 20.Click the *Finish* button."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/install-vm.md:54
msgid "In the top left of the window, click the *Begin Installation* button. The VM will start."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/install-vm.md:56
msgid "If it shows an error message saying *Unable to connect to libvirt qemu:///system* error, run:"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/install-vm.md:57
msgid ""
"<pre>\n"
"# On Debian-based operating systems\n"
"sudo systemctl enable --now libvirtd.service\n"
"\n"
"# On other operating systems\n"
"sudo systemctl enable --now libvirt.service\n"
"</pre>"
"\n"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/install-vm.md:65
msgid "If the VM fails to boot and shows the error *No bootable option or device found.*. Click Enter; this will start the UEFI user interface. Disable Secure Boot from the UEFI user interface: *Device Manager > Secure Boot Configuration > Attempt Secure Boot*, disable the checkbox by pressing the `Space` key. Click *Enter* to close the message box *Configuration changed*. Press `F10` to save, then `y`. Press the `Escape` key twice and select *Reset*."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/install-vm.md:67
msgid "Install the operating system to the second virtual disk, that means, in the *KDE Linux Installer* wizard, page *Partitions*, from the *Select storage device:* combo box select *vdb - 20 GiB*. After installing the OS is done, shut down the VM."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/install-vm.md:69
msgid "*VirtIO Disk 1* contains the raw file that you have downloaded."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/install-vm.md:71
msgid "Edit the VM configuration, right click on *VirtIO Disk 1* > Remove Hardware (decide if you want to also delete the raw file that you have downloaded), Delete."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/install-vm.md:73
msgid "Now, *VirtIO Disk 1* is the only virtual storage of the VM and contains the BTRFS storage where you have installed the KDE Linux operating system. Start the VM."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/install-vm.md:75
msgid "To connect to KDE Linux using SSH, you can enable the sshd systemd service:"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/install-vm.md:76
msgid ""
"<pre>\n"
"sudo systemctl enable --now sshd\n"
"</pre>"
"\n"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/install-vm.md:80
msgid "*Note: Clipboard sync from the VM to host (QEMU/virt-manager) does not work due to an upstream issue, though there is a [workaround](https://invent.kde.org/kde-linux/kde-linux/-/issues/445#note_1440608).*"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/install-vm.md:83
msgid "QEMU"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/install-vm.md:84
msgid "You can boot the raw file in a QEMU virtual machine:"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/install-vm.md:86
msgid ""
"<pre>\n"
"qemu-system-x86_64 -enable-kvm -m 4G -smp 4 \\\n  -drive if=pflash,format=raw,readonly=on,file=/usr/share/OVMF/x64/OVMF_CODE.4m.fd \\\n  -drive format=raw,file=kde-linux.raw\n"
"</pre>"
"\n"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/install-vm.md:93
msgid "XCP-ng"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/install-vm.md:95
msgid "In Xen Orchestra, select *Import > Disk*, choose a storage (not ISO) repository to hold the `.raw` file, drop the `.raw` file on the target, and upload it by selecting the *Import* button."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/install-vm.md:96
msgid "Select *New > VM* and choose the desired host pool."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/install-vm.md:97
msgid "Under *Info*, set *Template* to *Generic Linux UEFI* and enter a name."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/install-vm.md:98
msgid "Under *Performance*, choose CPU count (minimum 2, ideally 4+) and memory (minimum 2 GB, ideally 4+)."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/install-vm.md:99
msgid "Under *Install Settings*, select *PXE* (neither PXE nor ISO boot options will be used, but the form requires selecting one of the two)."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/install-vm.md:100
msgid "If no network interface is listed, select *Add Interface* to ensure that the VM has a network connection."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/install-vm.md:101
msgid "Under *Disks*, select the storage repository where the VM's virtual disk should be stored, and adjust the size to a reasonable amount (a minimum of 15 GiB is required)."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/install-vm.md:102
msgid "Under *Advanced*, select *Show Advanced Settings* and uncheck *Boot VM after creation*."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/install-vm.md:103
msgid "Select *Create* to finalize creation of the VM."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/install-vm.md:104
msgid "With the new VM's page showing in Xen Orchestra, select the *Disk* tab and select *Attach Disk*."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/install-vm.md:105
msgid "Select the `.raw` image from the drop down directly beneath the *New Disk* and *Attach Disk* buttons, check *Read Only*, then select *Attach*."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/install-vm.md:106
msgid "Select the *Advanced* tab, and under *Boot Order*, drag *Hard Disk* to the top and click *Save*."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/install-vm.md:107
msgid "Select the *Console* tab and start the VM."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/install-vm.md:108
msgid "Install KDE Linux using the *Install System* wizard in the live environment, then after the installation is completed, shut down the operating system to cleanly power off the VM."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/install-vm.md:109
msgid "Return to the Disks tab and use the *Remove VDI from this VM* icon button on the .raw file to remove the installation media from the VM."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/install-vm.md:110
msgid "The KDE Linux VM is now ready for use."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/install-vm.md:113
msgid "UTM (macOS)"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/install-vm.md:115
msgid "[UTM](https://mac.getutm.app/) is an open-source virtual machine app for macOS that uses QEMU under the hood."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/install-vm.md:118
msgid "Create a new virtual machine and select *Emulate*. Do **not** select *Virtualize*, as Apple's Virtualization framework is incompatible with the KDE Linux image."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/install-vm.md:119
msgid "Select *Linux* as the operating system."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/install-vm.md:120
msgid "Set memory and CPU cores. Enable *Display Output* and *Hardware OpenGL Acceleration*. ![UTM hardware settings](/linux/docs/utm1.png)"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/install-vm.md:122
msgid "For the boot device, select *ISO Image* and browse to the `.raw` file you downloaded. ![UTM boot device settings](/linux/docs/utm3.png)"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/install-vm.md:124
msgid "Set the storage size for the virtual drive."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/install-vm.md:125
msgid "Skip the shared directory setup and save the VM."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/install-vm.md:126
msgid "Open the VM settings. You will see two drives: the `.raw` image and the empty destination disk. Select the `.raw` drive and set *Image Type* to *Disk Image*, *Interface* to *USB*, and disable *Read Only*. ![UTM drive settings](/linux/docs/utm2.png)"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/install-vm.md:128
msgid "Save the settings and start the VM. Go through the KDE Linux installer."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/install-vm.md:129
msgid "After installation completes, shut down the VM, remove the `.raw` installer drive, and start the VM again. KDE Linux will boot from the installed disk."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/install-vm.md:0
msgid "Installing in a Virtual Machine"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/install.md:13
msgid ""
"{{< section class=\"text-center warning-bubble\" >}} Currently the Testing edition is available, showcasing the latest and greatest in-development versions of KDE’s [Plasma desktop environment](https://kde.org/plasma-desktop) and [apps](https://apps.kde.org). <br/>"
"<br/>"
" Expect frequent changes and regressions, and use it in a production environment at your own risk! <br/>"
"<br/>"
" Other editions suitable for the general public are in progress. {{< /section >}}"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/install.md:21
msgid "&nbsp;"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/install.md:23
msgid "Looking for instructions for installing KDE Linux in a virtual machine? [Find them here.](install-vm)"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/install.md:26
msgid "Requirements"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/install.md:27
msgid "KDE Linux supports almost all PC desktops and laptops with:"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/install.md:28
msgid "UEFI firmware (this includes most sold in the last 15 years)"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/install.md:29
msgid "An AMD or Intel CPU"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/install.md:30
msgid "2 GB of memory"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/install.md:31
msgid "15 GB of storage space"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/install.md:34
msgid "Known hardware limitations"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/install.md:35
msgid "**ARM-based CPUs:** e.g. Apple “M”-series CPUs and Qualcomm Snapdragon CPUs: not supported yet."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/install.md:36
msgid "**NVIDIA graphics cards**: cards from the “Turing” series or later (e.g. GTX 1630 or newer) work out of the box. Older cards are limited to the “Nouveau” driver, which [requires manual setup](pre-turing-nvidia/) ([learn more](/nvidia))."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/install.md:37
msgid "**Broadcom wireless cards**: [cards listed here](https://wireless.docs.kernel.org/en/latest/en/users/drivers/brcm80211.html#supported-chips) are supported out of the box. Other cards are not supported."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/install.md:38
msgid "**DisplayLink screens:** not supported. Display*Port* works fine."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/install.md:39
msgid "**Printers:** Most modern “driverless” and wireless printers made in the last 10 years or so — including [all listed here](https://openprinting.github.io/printers/) — will work out of the box. Drivers are included for many older wired printers, but not all. See the list of [known incompatible printers here](https://invent.kde.org/kde-linux/kde-linux/-/issues/?sort=created_date&state=opened&label_name[]=Hardware%20compatibility&label_name[]=Printers%20🔨)."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/install.md:42
msgid "Known software issues"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/install.md:43
msgid "See the items on the [list of significant limitations and known issues](https://invent.kde.org/groups/kde-linux/-/issues?sort=created_date&state=opened&label_name%5B%5D=Significant%20user-facing%20issue&not%5Blabel_name%5D%5B%5D=Hardware%20compatibility&first_page_size=100)."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/install.md:45
msgid "Ultimately the best way to determine KDE Linux’s suitability for your needs and hardware is to create a live USB drive and preview it on your own computer, with no risk to what’s already on it."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/install.md:48
msgid "1. Create a live USB drive"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/install.md:49
msgid "Download the latest `.raw` image from [here](https://files.kde.org/kde-linux/?C=M;O=D)."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/install.md:50
msgid "Verify that the `.raw` file is genuine: visit https://files.kde.org/kde-linux/?C=M;O=D and click *Details* for the .raw file you downloaded. Copy the long string of nonsense characters next to *SHA256* to the clipboard. Right-click on the downloaded `.raw` file on your computer, choose *Properties*, and then click on the *Checksums* tab. Paste the checksum from the website into the text field and press the `enter` key. Wait for the text field at the top to turn green. If it does, the file on your computer is the same one that you downloaded. If not, the file may be corrupt; try the download again."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/install.md:51
msgid "If the file is genuine, install [ISO Image Writer](https://apps.kde.org/isoimagewriter/) and launch it."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/install.md:52
msgid "Click “Path to ISO Image…” and locate the `.raw` file you downloaded."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/install.md:53
msgid "Plug in the USB flash drive and ensure it appears in the “To this USB Drive” area."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/install.md:54
msgid "Click “Create”."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/install.md:57
msgid "2. Prepare the target computer"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/install.md:58
msgid "Ensure that Secure Boot is disabled. If it isn’t, or you don’t know whether it is or not, enter the computer’s UEFI interface and disable it. Here’s how:"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/install.md:60
msgid "First, consult [the table here](https://forums.malwarebytes.com/topic/319165-pc-common-boot-menu-and-bios-setting-hotkeys/) and find the correct keyboard key under the “BIOS/UEFI Key” column for your brand of computer."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/install.md:61
msgid "To enter the UEFI interface, reboot the computer and repeatedly press that key while it starts up."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/install.md:62
msgid "Once you’re in the UEFI interface (you’ll know because it looks very ugly), find where it lets you turn off Secure Boot and turn it off. This is different for every UEFI implementation, so you may need to dig around a bit."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/install.md:63
msgid "Once you’ve turned off Secure Boot, find the “Exit and save changes” option, and use it."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/install.md:65
msgid "This requirement will go away in the future once [KDE Linux supports Secure Boot](https://invent.kde.org/kde-linux/kde-linux/-/issues/3)."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/install.md:68
msgid "3. Boot into the live USB drive"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/install.md:69
msgid "Plug in the USB drive."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/install.md:70
msgid "Consult [the table here](https://forums.malwarebytes.com/topic/319165-pc-common-boot-menu-and-bios-setting-hotkeys/) and note down the keyboard key under the “Boot Menu Key” column for your brand of computer."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/install.md:71
msgid "Reboot the computer and repeatedly press that key while it starts up."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/install.md:72
msgid "When the boot menu appears, use the Up or Down arrow keys to select the entry that looks like it describes your USB flash drive, and then press Enter."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/install.md:75
msgid "4. Explore the live session and install KDE Linux"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/install.md:76
msgid "Now you’re in the “Live Session” of KDE Linux! This lets you see what it will be like if you choose to install it. Go through the welcome wizard and then poke around to make sure everything you care about works. Plug in your typically-used devices and make sure they function properly."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/install.md:78
msgid "Once you’re ready to install, double-click on the “Install KDE Linux” icon on the desktop and go through the installer. Installing KDE Linux to the entire disk (erasing all existing data) is the most reliable option. Other installation methods may work, but are known to [fail under certain circumstances](https://invent.kde.org/kde-linux/kde-linux/-/work_items?label_name%5B%5D=Live%20session%2Finstaller) and are therefore **not recommended**."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/install.md:80
msgid "WARNING: if you choose to erase the computer’s hard disk, all of the files and data on it will be erased too. Make sure anything you care about is backed up somewhere!"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/install.md:83
msgid "5. Enjoy KDE Linux"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/install.md:84
msgid "We hope you love it!"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/install.md:0
msgid "Install KDE Linux"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/kde-dev.md:11
msgid "KDE Linux is an excellent development platform for KDE software. There are three primary paths, depending on how the KDE software you want to develop is shipped on KDE Linux:"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/kde-dev.md:12
msgid "[Developing KDE software that’s shipped on the base image](#build-kde-software-thats-shipped-on-the-base-image)"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/kde-dev.md:13
msgid "[Developing KDE software that can be built using Flatpak](#build-kde-app-with-a-flatpak-manifest)"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/kde-dev.md:14
msgid "[Developing any KDE software using Distrobox](#build-any-kde-software-using-kde-builder-in-distrobox)"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/kde-dev.md:18
msgid "Build KDE software that’s shipped on the base image"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/kde-dev.md:19
msgid "This workflow is used for developing KDE software that’s shipped on the base system, or even Qt. A list of such software [can be found here](https://invent.kde.org/kde-linux/kde-linux-packages/-/blob/master/make-pkgbuilds.py?ref_type=heads#L18) (note that “workspace” includes Plasma, KWin, and Plasma-aligned apps such as System Settings and Discover)."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/kde-dev.md:21
msgid "The best way to do this is by using <code>systemd-sysext</code>, which allows overlaying built-from-source content on top of <code>/usr/</code> without impacting the base system."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/kde-dev.md:23 content/docs/kde-dev.md:61
msgid "Setup"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/kde-dev.md:24
msgid "Run the setup script:"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/kde-dev.md:26
msgid ""
"<pre>\n"
"set-up-system-development\n"
"</pre>"
"\n"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/kde-dev.md:30
msgid "Use"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/kde-dev.md:31
msgid "In a nutshell, you’ll compile and install software using <code>kde-builder</code>, then refresh the systemd extension, and then finally restart any services that you changed (e.g. Plasma), or the entire system."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/kde-dev.md:33
msgid "For example, to compile and test a change to plasma-pa, do the following:"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/kde-dev.md:35
msgid ""
"<pre>\n"
"kde-builder plasma-pa\n"
"sudo systemd-sysext refresh --always-refresh=yes\n"
"systemctl restart --user plasma-plasmashell.service\n"
"</pre>"
"\n"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/kde-dev.md:41
msgid "If you replace a core system component and find that everything is crashing after the refresh is applied, try rebooting in order to fully reload the new dependency in all running software."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/kde-dev.md:43
msgid "When you’re finished developing or testing the change, disable (“un-merge”) the system extension:"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/kde-dev.md:45 content/docs/override-usr.md:40
msgid ""
"<pre>\n"
"sudo systemd-sysext unmerge\n"
"</pre>"
"\n"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/kde-dev.md:49
msgid "When you’re done with your built-from-source software (e.g. because it was accepted as a patch and merged), delete the installed files:"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/kde-dev.md:51
msgid ""
"<pre>\n"
"rm -r ~/kde/usr/*\n"
"# When you’re prompted to delete the read-only extension-release.kde file, answer 'n'\n"
"</pre>"
"\n"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/kde-dev.md:56
msgid "Build KDE app with a Flatpak manifest"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/kde-dev.md:57
msgid "To develop or test changes to the app code itself, build the app using <code>flatpak-builder</code>, so that the result is functionally identical to the app’s nightly Flatpak build."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/kde-dev.md:59
msgid "To develop or test changes to a KDE Framework or other library used by multiple apps, the only relatively painless approach at the moment is to use <code>kde-builder</code> to build them all. See [Developing KDE software that’s shipped on the base image](#build-kde-software-thats-shipped-on-the-base-image)."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/kde-dev.md:62
msgid "flatpak-builder will install flatpak packages from the remote flathub-apps-built-locally. This remote is the official Flathub store."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/kde-dev.md:64
msgid ""
"<pre>\n"
"flatpak remote-add --user --if-not-exists flathub-apps-built-locally https://flathub.org/repo/flathub.flatpakrepo\n"
"</pre>"
"\n"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/kde-dev.md:68
msgid "Make changes to just the app"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/kde-dev.md:69
msgid "First check out the source code for the KDE app you’d like to build. For example, here with Filelight:"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/kde-dev.md:71
msgid ""
"<pre>\n"
"# Create folder to hold KDE source code. Skippable if it already exists\n"
"mkdir -p ~/kde/src/\n"
"\n"
"# Go into that folder\n"
"cd ~/kde/src/\n"
"\n"
"# Download source code for Filelight\n"
"git clone git@invent.kde.org:utilities/filelight.git\n"
"\n"
"# Go into Filelight’s source code folder\n"
"cd ~/kde/src/filelight\n"
"\n"
"# Build Filelight as a flatpak\n"
"flatpak-builder build --user --install-deps-from=flathub-apps-built-locally --force-clean --ccache --install .flatpak-manifest.json\n"
"</pre>"
"\n"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/kde-dev.md:88
msgid "<code>flatpak-builder</code> will create a flatpak repo and remote named <code>filelight-origin</code> and export the freshly built Filelight flatpak to this flatpak repo."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/kde-dev.md:90
msgid "Now run it:"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/kde-dev.md:92
msgid ""
"<pre>\n"
"org.kde.filelight\n"
"</pre>"
"\n"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/kde-dev.md:96
msgid "For further information, see:"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/kde-dev.md:97
msgid "https://docs.flatpak.org/en/latest/getting-started.html"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/kde-dev.md:98
msgid "https://develop.kde.org/docs/packaging/flatpak/packaging/"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/kde-dev.md:101
msgid "Build any KDE software, using KDE Builder in Distrobox"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/kde-dev.md:102
msgid "If you need to work on some KDE software not preinstalled on the base system (so dependencies are also not pre-installed) that also does not or cannot build as a Flatpak, you can build it with <code>kde-builder</code> in a Distrobox:"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/kde-dev.md:104
msgid ""
"<pre>\n"
"# As per https://develop.kde.org/docs/getting-started/building/containers-distrobox\n"
"distrobox create --image docker.io/archlinux --name kdebuildercontainer --home ~/kdebuildercontainer_home\n"
"distrobox enter kdebuildercontainer\n"
"sudo pacman -Syu\n"
"sudo pacman -S nano\n"
"echo 'export PATH=\"$HOME/.local/bin:$PATH\"' | tee --append ~/.{bash,zsh}rc\n"
"exit\n"
"distrobox enter kdebuildercontainer\n"
"\n"
"# Install kde-builder as usual. https://develop.kde.org/docs/getting-started/building/kde-builder-setup\n"
"</pre>"
"\n"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/kde-dev.md:0
msgid "Develop KDE Software"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/kde-linux-dev.md:12
