msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/kde-linux-dev.md:18
msgid "**To get help with something related to KDE Linux**, [use discuss.kde.org](https://discuss.kde.org/), and tag your post with “kde-linux”."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/kde-linux-dev.md:21
msgid "CI Images"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/kde-linux-dev.md:22
msgid "Check the build log for your pipeline. It should mention where the images have been published."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/kde-linux-dev.md:24
msgid "You can also browse the images [from here](https://qoomon.github.io/aws-s3-bucket-browser/index.html?bucket=https://storage.kde.org/ci-artifacts/#kde-linux/kde-linux/)."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/kde-linux-dev.md:27
msgid "Improve Local Build Speed"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/kde-linux-dev.md:28
msgid "In order to speed up local builds, create a <code>mkosi.local.conf</code> file in the root of the repository with the following content:"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/kde-linux-dev.md:30
msgid ""
"<pre>\n"
"[Content]\n"
"Environment=LOCALE_GEN=\"en_US.UTF-8 UTF-8\" # replace with your locale`\n"
"Environment=MIRRORS_COUNTRY=us # replace with your country code`\n"
"Environment=PARALLEL_DOWNLOADS=50 # if your internet connection is fast\n"
"</pre>"
"\n"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/kde-linux-dev.md:37
msgid "You need to be using the Btrfs storage driver for docker, otherwise this won’t really work."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/kde-linux-dev.md:39
msgid "If your host filesystem uses Btrfs (like KDE Linux), add the following to /etc/docker/daemon.json"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/kde-linux-dev.md:41
msgid ""
"<pre>\n"
"{\n"
"  \"storage-driver\": \"btrfs\"\n"
"}\n"
"</pre>"
"\n"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/kde-linux-dev.md:47
msgid "Official docker documentation explaining this [can be found here](https://docs.docker.com/engine/storage/drivers/btrfs-driver/#configure-docker-to-use-the-btrfs-storage-driver)."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/kde-linux-dev.md:49
msgid "If you don’t use Btrfs for your host machine, you can still create a Btrfs volume backed by a file like so:"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/kde-linux-dev.md:51
msgid ""
"<pre>\n"
"systemctl stop docker.socket docker.service || true\n"
"fallocate -l 64G /store/docker.btrfs\n"
"mkfs.btrfs /store/docker.btrfs\n"
"[ -d /var/lib/docker ] || mkdir /var/lib/docker\n"
"mount /store/docker.btrfs /var/lib/docker\n"
"systemctl restart docker.socket docker.service\n"
"</pre>"
"\n"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/kde-linux-dev.md:60
msgid "Then run:"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/kde-linux-dev.md:62
msgid ""
"<pre>\n"
"./build_docker.sh --incremental\n"
"</pre>"
"\n"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/kde-linux-dev.md:66
msgid "Building Custom System Images"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/kde-linux-dev.md:68
msgid "You can generate custom KDE Linux images to test package integrations or system modifications locally. The build process uses <code>mkosi</code> wrapped in a Docker container."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/kde-linux-dev.md:70
msgid "To include custom packages, add the desired package names to the relevant configuration files (such as the <code>[Packages]</code> section in <code>mkosi.conf</code> or the specific <code>.packages</code> files) before running the build script."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/kde-linux-dev.md:72
msgid "Run the build with:"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/kde-linux-dev.md:74
msgid ""
"<pre>\n"
"./build_docker.sh\n"
"</pre>"
"\n"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/kde-linux-dev.md:78
msgid "Once the build finishes successfully, the output will be a <code>.raw</code> image file located in <code>mkosi.output/</code>."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/kde-linux-dev.md:80
msgid "Quick Testing with Virt-Manager"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/kde-linux-dev.md:82
msgid "The fastest way to test your changes is to boot the <code>.raw</code> image directly as an existing disk in a Virtual Machine, bypassing the full installation process."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/kde-linux-dev.md:84
msgid "Open *Virtual Machine Manager* and start the *New Virtual Machine* wizard."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/kde-linux-dev.md:85
msgid "Select *Import existing disk image* and choose your generated <code>.raw</code> file."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/kde-linux-dev.md:86
msgid "Allocate at least 4GB of RAM and 2 CPU cores."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/kde-linux-dev.md:87
msgid "**Important:** In the VM configuration, ensure the **Firmware** is set to **UEFI** and **Secure Boot** is disabled."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/kde-linux-dev.md:89
msgid "For a more permanent setup or instructions on using other virtualization tools like VirtualBox or UTM, refer to the [Installing in a Virtual Machine](./install-vm.md) guide."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/kde-linux-dev.md:0
msgid "Help develop KDE Linux"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/kernel-cmdline.md:11
msgid "At times it may be necessary to set additional command-line arguments for the kernel shipped with KDE Linux, and have them persist indefinitely — for example, to turn on experimental hardware or driver support, or enable hardware passthrough support for virtual machines."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/kernel-cmdline.md:13
msgid "{{< section class=\"text-center warning-bubble\" >}} <strong>Warning: this process is dangerous</strong>. Setting inappropriate kernel command-line arguments can reduce performance, increase energy usage, damage hardware components, or prevent the system from starting up."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/kernel-cmdline.md:16
msgid "Only proceed if you accept these risks, [have a backup](backup), and possess the technical ability to reverse any mistakes. {{< /section >}}"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/kernel-cmdline.md:19
msgid ""
"<br/>"
"\n"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/kernel-cmdline.md:21
msgid "If you’d like to proceed, here’s how:"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/kernel-cmdline.md:23
msgid ""
"Create the folder <tt>/boot/loader/addons/</tt> (only needs to be done once per system):<br/>"
" <code>run0 mkdir -p /boot/loader/addons/</code>"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/kernel-cmdline.md:26
msgid ""
"Create a kernel add-on containing the desired command-line arguments:<br/>"
" <code>run0 ukify build --cmdline '[arguments go here]' --output /boot/loader/addons/extra_args.addon.efi</code><br/>"
" Replace <code>[arguments go here]</code> with the actual command-line arguments. For example: <code>debug_objects</code>"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/kernel-cmdline.md:30
msgid "This add-on will then apply the additional kernel arguments for every boot, irrespective of which OS version the system is booted into."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/kernel-cmdline.md:32
msgid "If the add-on causes problems or is no longer needed, simply delete it:"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/kernel-cmdline.md:34
msgid "<code>run0 rm /boot/loader/addons/extra_args.addon.efi</code>"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/kernel-cmdline.md:38
msgid "A full list of supported command-line options [can be found here](https://www.kernel.org/doc/html/v4.14/admin-guide/kernel-parameters.html)."
