msgid "***This page is a work in progress.***"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/kernel-dev.md:13
msgid "KDE Linux provides a complete, preconfigured kernel development environment out of the box. No additional packages, containers, virtual machines, or chroots are required. Kernel development follows standard upstream Linux workflows, with a small number of integration steps specific to KDE Linux explained below."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/kernel-dev.md:16
msgid "Upstream documentation"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/kernel-dev.md:17
msgid "Kernel development on KDE Linux follows upstream Linux practices. Before proceeding, it is strongly recommended to become familiar with the official Linux kernel documentation:"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/kernel-dev.md:18
msgid "https://docs.kernel.org/"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/kernel-dev.md:19
msgid "https://docs.kernel.org/process/"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/kernel-dev.md:20
msgid "https://docs.kernel.org/kbuild/"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/kernel-dev.md:21
msgid "https://docs.kernel.org/rust/"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/kernel-dev.md:23
msgid "These documents describe the development process, coding style, build system, and (optionally) Rust support used by the kernel."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/kernel-dev.md:26
msgid "Prerequisites"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/kernel-dev.md:27
msgid "KDE Linux uses a read-only <code>/usr</code>. filesystem. Any custom kernel, kernel modules, or related artifacts must be installed via a writable overlay."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/kernel-dev.md:29
msgid "Before continuing, you **must** [set up a systemd system extension (sysext)](../override-usr) to allow overriding content in <code>/usr</code>."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/kernel-dev.md:31
msgid "This step is mandatory. All kernel images and modules built in this guide are installed into the sysext and then merged into the live system."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/kernel-dev.md:34
msgid "Cloning the Linux kernel"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/kernel-dev.md:35
msgid "Clone the upstream Linux kernel repository using Git:"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/kernel-dev.md:37
msgid ""
"<pre>\n"
"git clone https://git.kernel.org/pub/scm/linux/kernel/git/torvalds/linux.git\n"
"cd linux\n"
"</pre>"
"\n"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/kernel-dev.md:42
msgid "You may also clone a specific stable or development branch if required."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/kernel-dev.md:45
msgid "Kernel configuration"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/kernel-dev.md:46
msgid "You can start from the default configuration for your architecture:"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/kernel-dev.md:48
msgid ""
"<pre>\n"
"make defconfig\n"
"</pre>"
"\n"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/kernel-dev.md:52
msgid "To customize the configuration, use one of the standard kernel configuration interfaces:"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/kernel-dev.md:54
msgid ""
"<pre>\n"
"make menuconfig\n"
"make nconfig\n"
"make xconfig\n"
"</pre>"
"\n"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/kernel-dev.md:60
msgid "All configuration steps are identical to upstream Linux kernel development."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/kernel-dev.md:63
msgid "Building the kernel"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/kernel-dev.md:64
msgid "Build the kernel using the standard build system:"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/kernel-dev.md:66
msgid ""
"<pre>\n"
"make -j$(nproc)\n"
"</pre>"
"\n"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/kernel-dev.md:70
msgid "This produces the kernel image and modules in the build tree."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/kernel-dev.md:73
msgid "Installing into the sysext"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/kernel-dev.md:74
msgid "Install the kernel modules into the sysext overlay:"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/kernel-dev.md:76
msgid ""
"<pre>\n"
"make INSTALL_MOD_PATH=\"$HOME/kde/usr\" modules_install\n"
"</pre>"
"\n"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/kernel-dev.md:80
msgid "Determine the kernel version and install the kernel image:"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/kernel-dev.md:82
msgid ""
"<pre>\n"
"version=$(make -s kernelrelease)\n"
"install -Dm644 \"$(make -s image_name)\" \\\n  \"$HOME/kde/usr/lib/modules/$version/vmlinuz\"\n"
"</pre>"
"\n"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/kernel-dev.md:88
msgid "Refresh the systemd system extension so the system sees the new kernel and modules:"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/kernel-dev.md:90
msgid ""
"<pre>\n"
"run0 systemd-sysext refresh\n"
"</pre>"
"\n"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/kernel-dev.md:95
msgid "Rebuilding EFI images"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/kernel-dev.md:96
msgid "After installing the kernel into the sysext, rebuild the EFI artifacts based on the updated <code>/usr</code> contents:"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/kernel-dev.md:98
msgid ""
"<pre>\n"
"run0 /usr/lib/rebuild-efi\n"
"</pre>"
"\n"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/kernel-dev.md:102
msgid "This step generates a new Unified Kernel Image (UKI)."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/kernel-dev.md:105
msgid "Installing the Unified Kernel Image"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/kernel-dev.md:107
msgid "Install the generated UKI into the EFI System Partition:"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/kernel-dev.md:109
msgid ""
"<pre>\n"
"run0 cp kde-linux.efi /boot/EFI/Linux/\n"
"</pre>"
"\n"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/kernel-dev.md:113
msgid "The new kernel will appear as an unversioned entry in systemd-boot and can be selected at the next boot."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/kernel-dev.md:0
msgid "Kernel Development"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/low-latency.md:11
msgid "Some apps benefits from being run with very *low latency*, or low potential for lag, stutter, and interruptions from other running software. Most apps don’t need this — not even video games — but some do, including those for professional audio production."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/low-latency.md:13
msgid "In KDE Linux, apps are allowed to ask for low latency privileges themselves. Any that don’t can be given these privileges manually. If you encounter lag or stuttering in performance-critical apps, here are some methods of doing that:"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/low-latency.md:15
msgid "Give a specific app or process low latency privileges"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/low-latency.md:16
msgid "Launch the app you want to apply low latency privileges to, if it’s not already running."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/low-latency.md:17
msgid "Open *System Monitor*."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/low-latency.md:18
msgid "Locate the app or process on the *Applications* or *Processes* page."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/low-latency.md:19
msgid "Right-click on it and click *Set Priority…*."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/low-latency.md:20
msgid "In the dialog window that appears, increase the sliders’ priority values and click on the radio buttons for “FIFO” and “Real Time”."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/low-latency.md:22
msgid "Give all apps or processes low latency privileges"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/low-latency.md:23
msgid "Put your user account in the `realtime` group by running <code>sudo useradd -G realtime -m $(whoami)</code> in a terminal window."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/low-latency.md:25
msgid "Note that this is a fairly drastic solution. It may be better to create a new user account, put *that* user in the `realtime` group, and only log into that user account to run low-latency-critical apps."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/low-latency.md:0
msgid "Reduce Latency for Specialized Software"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/migrate-older.md:11
msgid "2024-12-01 image or earlier"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/migrate-older.md:12
msgid "To update a system installed from this or an earlier image, run the following in a terminal window:"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/migrate-older.md:14
msgid ""
"<pre>\n"
"git clone https://invent.kde.org/kde-linux/kde-linux\n"
"cd kde-linux\n"
"run0 ./update.sh update\n"
"</pre>"
"\n"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/migrate-older.md:21
msgid "2025-08-04 image or earlier"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/migrate-older.md:22
msgid "To adopt the erofs-based <code>/usr</code> on a system installed from the 2025-08-04 image or earlier, first update to the 2025-08-05 image or later, then create a file named <code>/etc/sysupdate.d/erofs.feature.d/enable.conf</code> containing the following:"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/migrate-older.md:24
msgid ""
"<pre>\n"
"[Feature]\n"
"Enabled=true\n"
"</pre>"
"\n"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/migrate-older.md:29
msgid "And then run:"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/migrate-older.md:30
msgid ""
"<pre>\n"
"run0 /usr/lib/systemd/systemd-sysupdate update\n"
"</pre>"
"\n"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/migrate-older.md:34
msgid "After a reboot, <code>/usr</code> will be a read-only erofs volume, and the rest of <code>/</code> will be writable by the root user."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/migrate-older.md:36
msgid "See [Overview of RootFS v2](https://community.kde.org/KDE_Linux/RootFSv2) for an overview of this change, and manual migration instructions should the automatic migration fail."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/migrate-older.md:0
msgid "Migrate older installations"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/more-software.md:11
msgid "If you don't find the software you're looking for in Discover, there are a few options here, depending on what you want. All of these options are more suitable for advanced users."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/more-software.md:13
msgid "Specific common software"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/more-software.md:14
msgid "DaVinci Resolve"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/more-software.md:15
msgid "DaVinci Resolve is challenging to install. If it meets your needs, consider trying KDE's [Kdenlive](https://kdenlive.org) video editor instead. If not, proceed."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/more-software.md:17
msgid "First, download the DaVinci Resolve software using the official installer at https://www.blackmagicdesign.com/products/davinciresolve. This will get you a <code>.run</code> file. Ignore it for now."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/more-software.md:19
msgid "If you are using an NVIDIA GPU, run the following commands in a terminal window:"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/more-software.md:20
msgid ""
"<pre>\n"
"distrobox create -i ghcr.io/zelikos/davincibox:latest --nvidia -n davincibox\n"
"[drag the .run file into the terminal window, or paste its path here] --appimage-extract\n"
"distrobox enter davincibox -- sudo dnf update\n"
"</pre>"
"\n"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/more-software.md:26
msgid "Otherwise, if you are not using an NVIDIA GPU, run the commands below instead:"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/more-software.md:27
msgid ""
"<pre>\n"
"wget https://raw.githubusercontent.com/zelikos/davincibox/refs/heads/main/setup.sh --directory-prefix=/tmp/\n"
"chmod +x /tmp/setup.sh\n"
"/tmp/setup.sh [drag the .run file into the terminal window, or paste its path here]\n"
"</pre>"
"\n"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/more-software.md:33
msgid "For more information, see https://github.com/zelikos/davincibox/."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/more-software.md:35
msgid "Tailscale"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/more-software.md:36
msgid "Follow one of the following sets of instructions:"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/more-software.md:37
msgid "https://github.com/suikan4github/Using-tailscale-client-on-an-Immutable-OS (Uses Distrobox)"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/more-software.md:38
msgid "https://github.com/xuars/kdelinux-tailscale (Downloads binaries to /opt)"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/more-software.md:40
msgid "Software not listed above"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/more-software.md:41
msgid "Distrobox"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/more-software.md:42
msgid "[Distrobox](https://distrobox.it) is a system for creating “containers” within which you can install anything from the software library of another Linux distribution, in a self-contained manner and with access to the files in your home directory. Distrobox works well for creating bespoke development environments that won't scatter files all over your home directory. Distrobox comes pre-installed in KDE Linux; explore it using the <code>distrobox</code> command-line. [Toolbx](https://containertoolbx.org) is also pre-installed and supported."
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/more-software.md:44
msgid "Example usage:"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/more-software.md:46
msgid ""
"<pre>\n"
"# Try to run a command, for example \"mc\"\n"
"mc\n"
"\n"
"# It does not work because is not installed on the system\n"
"# KDE Linux does not include the “mc” command.\n"
"\n"
"# Download the image \"quay.io/toolbx/arch-toolbox\".\n"
"distrobox create -n default\n"
"\n"
"# Enter it\n"
"distrobox enter default\n"
"\n"
"# Do whatever you want in it. Here, we install `mc`\n"
"sudo pacman -Syu\n"
"sudo pacman -S mc\n"
"\n"
"# Run `mc`. Your home directory from KDE Linux is exposed as your home directory inside the Linux container. Press F10 to close mc.\n"
"mc\n"
"\n"
"# Exit the distrobox container\n"
"</pre>"
"\n"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/more-software.md:69
msgid ""
"<pre>\n"
"# To find the container image:\n"
"podman image list\n"
"\n"
"# To see the distrobox podman container still running:\n"
"podman ps\n"
"distrobox list\n"
"distrobox stop default\n"
"\n"
"# To delete the container:\n"
"distrobox rm name\n"
"podman image list # Says \"IMAGE ID\" is 664c1f5776fa.\n"
"podman image rm 664c1f5776fa\n"
"podman image list\n"
"</pre>"
"\n"
msgstr ""

