#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/python-dev.md:11
msgid "KDE Linux includes Python, but without any provision for installing additional system-level modules. Many Python programs require the use of modules that aren’t pre-installed, so how do you resolve this situation?"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/python-dev.md:13
msgid "The solution is to create a virtual environment, within which you can install whatever dependencies you need:"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/python-dev.md:15
msgid ""
"<pre>\n"
"# Create a new virtual environment in the current directory named “venv”\n"
"python -m venv venv\n"
"\n"
"# Activate the “venv” virtual environment\n"
"source venv/bin/activate\n"
"\n"
"# Install what you need\n"
"python -m ensurepip --default-pip\n"
"pip install [whatever Python modules you need]\n"
"\n"
"# run or develop the tool\n"
"\n"
"# Exit the virtual environment\n"
"deactivate\n"
"\n"
"# Optional: delete the “venv” virtual environment if you don’t need it anymore\n"
"rm -r venv\n"
"</pre>"
"\n"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/python-dev.md:36
msgid "{{< section class=\"text-center warning-bubble\" >}} It’s recommended to avoid installing Python using Homebrew, as this will [break kde-builder](https://invent.kde.org/kde-linux/kde-linux/-/issues/278) and potentially any other Python-based software shipped on the system. {{< /section >}}"
msgstr ""

#. +> trunk5
#: content/docs/python-dev.md:0
msgid "Develop or Run Python scripts"
msgstr ""

